{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499893"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:04:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:04:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1577"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1577"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.57,0.24,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52295"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1577"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37633"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"850"},{"type":"contributions","id":"903"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1315"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14752"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14957"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42344"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52295"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a 12-month history of depression, weakness and weight gain. The weight gain is significantly increased on the face, shoulders and abdomen. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 150/94 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. She has plethoric facies (Image) and obvious abdominal stretch marks.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line investigation to confirm this diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["24-hour urine catecholamines","Low-dose dexamethasone suppression test","Early morning serum cortisol","High-dose dexamethasone suppression test","Petrosal sinus sampling"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of Cushing\u0027s syndrome, including central obesity, facial plethora, abdominal striae, hypertension, and mood changes. Given these findings, appropriate testing to confirm the diagnosis is crucial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elow-dose dexamethasone suppression test\u003C/strong\u003E is considered the most appropriate first-line investigation for suspected Cushing\u0027s syndrome. This test involves administering a low dose of dexamethasone (usually 1 mg) at 11 PM and measuring serum cortisol at 8 AM the following morning. In normal individuals, the exogenous glucocorticoid should suppress endogenous cortisol production. Failure to suppress indicates Cushing\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urine catecholamines\u003C/strong\u003E are used to diagnose phaeochromocytoma, not Cushing\u0027s syndrome. While phaeochromocytoma can cause some similar symptoms (like hypertension), it typically presents with episodic symptoms and would not explain this patient\u0027s cushingoid appearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eearly morning serum cortisol\u003C/strong\u003E measurement alone is not sufficient to diagnose Cushing\u0027s syndrome. Cortisol levels fluctuate throughout the day and can be affected by stress, making a single measurement unreliable for diagnosis. Late night salivary cortisol can be used as a screening test for Cushing\u0027s syndrome. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh-dose dexamethasone suppression test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to differentiate between pituitary and ectopic sources of ACTH in confirmed cases of ACTH-dependent Cushing\u0027s syndrome. It is not a first-line test for diagnosing Cushing\u0027s syndrome itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPetrosal sinus sampling\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure used to localise the source of ACTH production in confirmed cases of Cushing\u0027s disease (pituitary-dependent Cushing\u0027s syndrome). It is not used as a first-line diagnostic test for Cushing\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter confirming the diagnosis with the low-dose dexamethasone suppression test, further investigations would be needed to determine the cause of Cushing\u0027s syndrome (pituitary, adrenal, or ectopic). These might include measurement of ACTH levels, imaging studies, and potentially the high-dose dexamethasone suppression test or petrosal sinus sampling, depending on initial results.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cushing\u0027s syndrome presents with central obesity, facial plethora, and abdominal striae.","Late night salivary cortisol, 24hour urinary free cortisol, and low dose dexamethasone suppression test, can all be used as part of the initial screening process where there is a suspicion of Cushing\u0027s syndrome."],"references":["Diagnosis of Cushing\u2019s Syndrome [Internet]. www.adrenal.com. Available from: https://www.adrenal.com/cushing-syndrome/diagnosis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37633"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1577"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18468"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18468"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ce963c28-7092-4d66-aa6e-dfd860b746c3.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ce963c28-7092-4d66-aa6e-dfd860b746c3.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":397,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37633"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-03T18:11:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-03T18:22:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1577"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52295"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":